When someone is in a position to make a difference in conservation and solely base his decision on what is best for the species, however controversial, this is the result. 

Michael Fouraker is the director of Fort Worth Zoo—-one of the best zoo in the world. Fort Worth Zoo is the sole “owner” of all legal Anegada iguanas (Cyclura pinguis) in the USA. 

They were loaned to various zoos so that they can be produced and, ultimately, placed back on a chosen island as an insurance population. 

Unfortunately, last one was produced 11 years ago and numbers have steadily shrunk to only 11 animals in the US—-of which only 4 are females. One female has recently been spayed—-leaving us with 3 possibly reproductive females. 

Mike has asked us to take on the task of taking possession of 3 remaining females and 3 males to produce enough to sustain and ultimately produce enough to repopulate an island. There are only 200-300 Cyclura pinguis left in the whole world. 

This decision is not supported by many in the zoological institutions as most AZA zoo do not want animals going to a “commercial breeder.” 

This privilege to work with this critically endangered species won’t be taken lightly and we will do everything we can to prove to the skeptics that a private breeder can work with public zoos for conservation. Obviously this species won’t be commercialized and Iguanaland will provide all funds needed to house, keep and produce this species for the good of the species future. I won’t be alone with this project as I will be working with Fort Worth Zoo, Miami Zoo and my trusty veterinarian and Cyclura consultant, Sean M. Perry DVM, PhD. Thank you Mike for trusting us with this project!
Showing off some of our Cuora species we have here at Iguanaland.

Species highlight: The twist-necked turtle (Platemys platycephala is a small (6-8”) species found in shallow creeks and on forest floors of central and northern South America. Our animals spend more time on land then in our shallow pond, thus should be given relatively large land area. In the wild, they feed upon fish, snails, amphibians, insects and worms and some vegetation. In captivity, they can be fed on commercial turtle pellets and omnivore diet. Most specimens available are imported as they are not easy to acclimate and I know of only few instances of successful captive breeding. Our animals are kept outdoors year around with water temperature of 70-80.

Educating the children and fanning their passion for reptiles is at the heart of what we do here at Iguanaland.

We just booked a field trip for 90 homeschoolers and their parents. Iguanaland first mission is to educate the children and public on the importance of reptiles to nature and humanity. To general public, reptiles are still seen as something to be avoided. They are perceived as dangerous, toxic, venomous—-even unclean. This misconception are generally reinforced by roadside zoos. We built iguanaland to show our guests that reptiles are beautiful, harmless and approachable.

Varanus salvadorii: the crocodile monitor, is a species of monitor lizard endemic to New Guinea. It is one of the longest lizards in the world and some claims that it is longer than the Komodo dragons but of course much less heavier as crocodile monitors are mostly arboreal.

The flowerback box turtle (Cuora galbinifrons) is a species of Asian box turtles from China (Hainan and Guangxi), northern and central Vietnam, Laos, and possibly northeastern Cambodia. This species is considered to be critically endangered.
The painted terrapin (Batagur borneoensis) is a critically endangered species from the rainforest of Brunei, Indonesia (Sumatra and Kalimantan), Malaysia, and Thailand. The male is in breeding color.

The giant Asian pond turtle (Heosemys grandis) living the best life, here at Iguanaland. This critically endangered species occurs throughout Cambodia and Vietnam and in parts of Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar and Thailand.

Iguanafest is a fundraiser for Iguana conservation. There are ~45 species of Iguanas in the world and more than 2/3 are endangered. 

Our 3rd Iguanafest will be on October 14, 2023 at Iguanaland in Punta Gorda FL. 

The sponsorship levels are $500 (green iguana), $1000 (Chuckwalla), $1500 (spiny-tailed iguana), $2500 (rock iguana) and $5000 (Fiji iguana). The rock and Fiji iguana level will get your logo on the back of the shirts and all other advertising materials and green iguana, chuckwalla  and spiny-tailed iguana levels will get mentioned in all our advertising materials including all display signs. We have partnered with Gladys Porter Zoo to make sure that your donation is tax deductible. 

https://www.iguanaland.com/events/iguanafest

Cuban iguana (Cyclura nubila nubila) eggs: this species can sold over the state line, only if you can prove that the line came from Puerto Rico or you have the ESA permit from USF&W. 

We can prove that all our lines are from Puerto Rico. We should have about 60 babies hatching this year—-starting about two weeks from now. 

Please know the law before purchasing.

2023 banana pectinata. One of my favorite specie of spiny-tailed iguana. My line stays small as adults—-typically growing to about 18 inches for the females and 30 for the big males. I do have bunch ready ✈️ as we produced close to 100 this year.

Article on exotic species in FL by Benji Jones on VOX. I tried to explain my view, which is that our ecosystem will adapt to introduced species. I firmly believe that no native species will go exotic due to introduced species and nature will balance itself out. 

I thank Benji for listening to our views and writing an article that is balanced rather than one side view that has been portraying by FWC and media.

I think Sunday afternoon is a perfect time to announce that my buddy’s book, Turtling, will be out for EVERYONE, to purchase on October 10. His first public signing will be at Iguanafest on October 14 at Iguanaland. Here is a short snippet from his email to me recently:

“TURTLING: Following my Passion covers both my personal and professional experiences as I traveled throughout the world and is delivered to the reader in an informative, enlightening, and entertaining memoir for young entrepreneurs, pet industry people, turtle conservationists and reptile enthusiasts alike.

 

Ty, you know me best; I do NOT want to get into any limelight, marketing my book along with numerous book signings and promotions.

My main purpose in writing it was for myself but as I refined the entire memoir, I saw that there was positively marketability especially within the reptile and pet industry as well as young entrepreneurs looking for direction. As a result, I have identified six (6) turtle and tortoise conservation non-profits who I will be donating royalty proceeds to on an annual basis.”

Yup—-all proceeds will benefit conservation!!!!

Today, it’s the 4th graders visiting Iguanaland. Anna spent almost an hour with them as they were so curious with so many questions. Our mission is to change fear to curiosity; curiosity to knowledge; knowledge to love and conservation. Our program starts with them free roaming the zoo for an hour or so, then we bring them in for a class with different animals and then they will have lunch and more roaming, before going back to school with full of new knowledge about these precious but misunderstood animals.

Joe ended up collecting 12 fertile eggs from our Sumbawa water monitor at 3 am in the morning. They will be incubated at 86 degrees and should be hatching in about 6 months. She did lay a nice clutch of 10 eggs on 8/28 that should hatch around the end of January or beginning of February. Our Sambawa pair were imported animals that I purchased as babies.
